  "summary": "McArthur concludes a lengthy deduction by suggesting that Kumagai might be the great-grandson of Medvedev. He posits that Medvedev had a mistress in Japan who was pregnant when his body was found, and that this descendant might be seeking revenge against the Inagaki family. Detective Jouji is visibly affected by this theory, but McArthur clarifies it was merely a reliable scenario for investigation.\n\nThe meeting is interrupted by Kuwabara, who enters the room clapping. Kuwabara (referred to elsewhere as Wakuzukin or Mukagawa) refutes the accusation, stating his background is clear and that Medvedev’s actual great-grandchild is female. Despite McArthur’s attempt to suggest Kuwabara might be motivated by Kanai's inheritance, the group loses confidence in the detective. Mutsu dismisses the meeting, leaving a defeated McArthur behind.\n\nFollowing the meeting, the narrator reunites with Matsuzaki, who has returned from a mountain retreat at Mount Kumashira. The narrator recounts the recent murders of Mirei and Kanae, and the revelation that Yuzuha is Kikyo. Mutsu reflects on the case, noting that while he felt powerless, the experience provided him with a sense of personal growth. Mutsu also warns McArthur to be careful in the future, noting that McArthur's intelligence makes him dangerous.\n\nLater, Mutsu takes the narrator to National K University Hospital. Mutsu reveals he has an appointment with Professor Nakatani, a world-renowned pioneer in Japanese neuroscience, though he does not immediately disclose his specific motive for the visit.",
